    "What do you observe? Is this consistent with Zipf's law?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Zipf's law states that given a large sample of words used, the frequency of any word is inversely proportional to its rank in the frequency table. So word number N has a frequency of N. Thus the most frequent word will occur about twice as often as the second most frequent word, three times as often as the third most frequent word, etc. We observe that the data above follows the Zipf's law."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Part 1.2: Feature Represenation (10 points)\n",
    "\n",
    "In this part you will build feature vectors for each review. This will be input to our ML classifiers. You should call your parser from earlier, using all the same assumptions (e.g., casefolding, stemming). Each feature value should be the term count for that review."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 66,
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": true
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from sklearn.feature_extraction import DictVectorizer\n",
    "token_counter = []\n",
    "for t in token_list:\n",
    "    token_counter.append(dict(Counter(t)))\n",
    "vec = DictVectorizer()\n",
    "feature_vectors = vec.fit_transform(token_counter)\n",
    "# print(feature_vectors.shape)"
   ]
